    <h3>Key Features of Java:</h3>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Platform Independence:</strong> Java code is compiled into an intermediate form called bytecode, which can be executed on any device equipped with a JVM. This "write once, run anywhere" capability is a significant advantage.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Object-Oriented:</strong> Java is built around the concept of objects. This allows developers to create modular programs and reusable code. Key concepts include classes, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Robust and Secure:</strong> Java includes strong memory management, exception handling, and type checking at compile time. It also includes security features such as bytecode verification and a security manager that allows applications to define security policies.</li>
        <li><strong>Simple and Familiar Syntax:</strong> Java's syntax is influenced by C and C++, making it relatively easy to learn for those familiar with these languages. However, it omits many complex and error-prone features of C++, such as pointers and multiple inheritance.
        </li>
        <li><strong>Multithreaded:</strong> Java supports multithreading, which allows multiple threads to run concurrently, enabling the development of interactive and high-performance applications.</li>
        <li><strong>Rich Standard Library:</strong> Java comes with an extensive standard library that provides many utilities and frameworks for common tasks, such as data structures, networking, database access, and graphical user interface (GUI) development.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Java Development Components</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Java Development Kit (JDK): The JDK is a software development kit used to develop Java applications. It includes the Java Runtime Environment (JRE), an interpreter/loader (Java), a compiler (javac), an archiver (jar), a documentation generator (Javadoc), and other tools needed for Java development.</li>
        <li>Java Runtime Environment (JRE): The JRE provides libraries, the JVM, and other components necessary to run applications written in Java. It does not contain tools for Java development, such as compilers or debuggers.</li>
        <li>Java Virtual Machine (JVM): The JVM is an abstract computing machine that enables a computer to run a Java program. It provides the necessary environment for Java bytecode to be executed, which includes memory management and garbage collection.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Java Editions</h3>

    <ul>
        <li>Java SE (Standard Edition): This is the core Java platform used for developing desktop applications and server environments. It includes the JDK, JVM, and a set of libraries.</li>
        <li>Java EE (Enterprise Edition): Built on top of Java SE, Java EE provides an API and runtime environment for developing and running large-scale, multi-tiered, scalable, and secure network applications. It includes additional libraries for database access, web services, and more.</li>
        <li>Java ME (Micro Edition): This edition is designed for embedded systems and mobile devices, offering a subset of the features of Java SE.</li>
    </ul>


